"update": 1,
"values": [ "", "[center]Hi, I’m Joe from the [b]Gaming Accessibility 
Team at Xbox.[/b]
[/center]", "[center]2021 was such a [wave amp=50 freq=2]great year for gaming accessibility[/wave]
– and we can’t wait to see the progress
[/center]", "[center]that’ll be made in [rainbow freq=0.2 sat=10 val=20]2022[/rainbow].
[/center]", "[center]Here are the top 5 tips to keep in mind when
creating accessible games this year.
[/center]", "[center]Number 1 – Plan ahead!
[/center]", "[center]Define your accessibility goals early on in
the product lifecycle.
[/center]", "[center]Truly accessible gaming experiences are built
by design, and not as last-minute add-ons.
[/center]", "[center]This means that additional features added
later on in the development cycle to fix inaccessible
[/center]", "[center]designs are not always effective for players.
[/center]", "[center]Number 2 – Don’t design yourself into
a corner!
[/center]", "[center]Let’s say your team wants to ensure that
players can scale text up to 200% (which you
[/center]", "[center]should!), but during development, your game
is hard coded to the default text size – meaning
[/center]", "[center]once text is scaled, the UI breaks.
[/center]", "[center]By using variables as often as possible in
your programming, and creating mockups of
[/center]", "[center]the extreme variables to make sure they’re
going to work, you can save a lot of time
[/center]", "[center]and deliver an experience that works.
[/center]", "[center]Number 3 – Think about who you may be excluding.
[/center]", "[center]For example, if you make a choice to require
quick, repetitive button choices on the controller
[/center]", "[center]as a core mechanic of your game, you may unintentionally
exclude players who cannot physically perform
[/center]", "[center]those actions.
[/center]", "[center]In contrast, if you allow players to customize
the input type for certain actions, like introducing
[/center]", "[center]other options such as “quick button hold,”
or allowing players to skip rapid button presses,
[/center]", "[center]this will help eliminate barriers.
[/center]", "[center]Number 4 – Partner with the gaming and disability
community.
[/center]", "[center]If you don’t know whether or not your design
decisions might be excluding groups of players,
[/center]", "[center]you can work with disabled gamers who can
help you find ways to eliminate the barriers.
[/center]", "[center]Number 5 – Test early and test often!
[/center]", "[center]When it comes to accessibility, it’s important
to identify barriers to access as early as
[/center]", "[center]possible in order to allow time to properly
build solutions.
[/center]", "[center]While it can seem tempting to wait until a
playable build of the game is ready to gather
[/center]", "[center]feedback, at this point, it might be too late
to implement the nature of feedback you may
[/center]", "[center]get from the gaming and disability community.
[/center]", "[center]Let’s recap.
[/center]", "[center]Number 1, Plan ahead.
[/center]", "[center]Number 2, Don’t design yourself into a corner.
[/center]", "[center]Number 3, Think about who you may be excluding.
[/center]", "[center]Number 4, Partner with the gaming and disability
community.
[/center]", "[center]And number 5, Test early and often.
[/center]", "[center]Let’s make 2022 the best year for accessible
gaming.
[/center]", "[center]Thanks for watching!
[/center]", "" ]
}

